# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: loguru-logging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Core logging functionalities of the *Loguru* library.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] An object to dispatch logging messages to configured handlers.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `Logger` is the core object of `loguru`, every logging configuration and usage pass through a call to one of its methods.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] There is only one logger, so there is no need to retrieve one before usage.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Once the `logger` is imported, it can be used to write messages about events happening in your code.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] By reading the output logs of your application, you gain a better understanding of the flow of your program and you more easily track and debug unexpected behaviors.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Handlers to which the logger sends log messages are added using the `add()` method.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that you can use the `Logger` right after import as it comes pre-configured (logs are emitted to `sys.stderr` by default).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Messages can be logged with different severity levels and they can be formatted using curly braces (it uses `str.format()` under the hood).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] When a message is logged, a “record” is associated with it.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This record is a dict which contains information about the logging context: time, function, file, line, thread, level… It also contains the `__name__` of the module, this is why you don’t need named loggers.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] You should not instantiate a `Logger` by yourself, use `from loguru import logger` instead.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Add a handler sending log messages to a sink adequately configured.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `int` – An identifier associated with the added sink and which should be used to `remove()` it.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `sink` handles incoming log messages and proceed to their writing somewhere and somehow.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that the logging functions are not reentrant.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This means you should avoid using the `logger` inside any of your sinks or from within `signal` handlers.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Otherwise, you may face deadlock if the module’s sink was not explicitly disabled.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The logged message passed to all added sinks is nothing more than a string of the formatted log, to which a special attribute is associated: the `.record` which is a dict containing all contextual information possibly needed (see below).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Logged messages are formatted according to the `format` of the added sink.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This format is usually a string containing braces fields to display attributes from the record dict.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If fine-grained control is needed, the `format` can also be a function which takes the record as parameter and return the format template string.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] However, note that in such a case, you should take care of appending the line ending and exception field to the returned format, while `"\n{exception}"` is automatically appended for convenience if `format` is a string.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `filter` attribute can be used to control which messages are effectively passed to the sink and which one are ignored.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] A function can be used, accepting the record as an argument, and returning `True` if the message should be logged, `False` otherwise.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If a string is used, only the records with the same `name` and its children will be allowed.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] One can also pass a `dict` mapping module names to minimum required level.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] In such case, each log record will search for it’s closest parent in the `dict` and use the associated level as the filter.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `dict` values can be `int` severity, `str` level name or `True` and `False` to respectively authorize and discard all module logs unconditionally.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] In order to set a default level, the `""` module name should be used as it is the parent of all modules (it does not suppress global `level` threshold, though).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that while calling a logging method, the keyword arguments (if any) are automatically added to the `extra` dict for convenient contextualization (in addition to being used for formatting).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Each logged message is associated with a severity level.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] These levels make it possible to prioritize messages and to choose the verbosity of the logs according to usages.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] For example, it allows to display some debugging information to a developer, while hiding it to the end user running the application.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `level` attribute of every added sink controls the minimum threshold from which log messages are allowed to be emitted.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] While using the `logger`, you are in charge of configuring the appropriate granularity of your logs.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] It is possible to add even more custom levels by using the `level()` method.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The record is just a Python dict, accessible from sinks by `message.record`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] It contains all contextual information of the logging call (time, function, file, line, level, etc.).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Each of the record keys can be used in the handler’s `format` so the corresponding value is properly displayed in the logged message (e.g.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Some records’ values are objects with two or more attributes.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] These can be formatted with `"{key.attr}"` (`"{key}"` would display one by default).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that you can use any formatting directives available in Python’s `str.format()` method (e.g.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `"{key: >3}"` will right-align and pad to a width of 3 characters).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This is particularly useful for time formatting (see below).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To use your favorite time representation, you can set it directly in the time formatter specifier of your handler format, like for example `format="{time:HH:mm:ss} {message}"`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that this datetime represents your local time, and it is also made timezone-aware, so you can display the UTC offset to avoid ambiguities.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The time field can be formatted using more human-friendly tokens.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] These constitute a subset of the one used by the Pendulum library of @sdispater.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To escape a token, just add square brackets around it, for example `"[YY]"` would display literally `"YY"`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If you prefer to display UTC rather than local time, you can add `"!UTC"` at the very end of the time format, like `{time:HH:mm:ss!UTC}`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Doing so will convert the `datetime` to UTC before formatting.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If no time formatter specifier is used, like for example if `format="{time} {message}"`, the default one will use ISO 8601.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If the sink is a `str` or a `pathlib.Path`, the corresponding file will be opened for writing logs.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The path can also contain a special `"{time}"` field that will be formatted with the current date at file creation.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The file is closed at sink stop, i.e. when the application ends or the handler is removed.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `rotation` check is made before logging each message.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If there is already an existing file with the same name that the file to be created, then the existing file is renamed by appending the date to its basename to prevent file overwriting.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `retention` occurs at rotation or at sink stop if rotation is `None`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Files resulting from previous sessions or rotations are automatically collected from disk.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] A file is selected if it matches the pattern `"basename(.*).ext(.*)"` (possible time fields are beforehand replaced with `.*`) based on the configured sink.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Afterwards, the list is processed to determine files to be retained.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `compression` happens at rotation or at sink stop if rotation is `None`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Either way, if you use a custom function designed according to your preferences, you must be very careful not to use the `logger` within your function.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Otherwise, there is a risk that your program hang because of a deadlock.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To add colors to your logs, you just have to enclose your format string with the appropriate tags (e.g.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] These tags are automatically removed if the sink doesn’t support ansi codes.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] For convenience, you can use `</>` to close the last opening tag without repeating its name (e.g.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The special tag `<level>` (abbreviated with `<lvl>`) is transformed according to the configured color of the logged message level.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Tags which are not recognized will raise an exception during parsing, to inform you about possible misuse.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If you wish to display a markup tag literally, you can escape it by prepending a `\` like for example `\<blue>`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To prevent the escaping to occur, you can simply double the `\` (e.g.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `\\<blue>` will print a literal `\` before colored text).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If, for some reason, you need to escape a string programmatically, note that the regex used internally to parse markup tags is `r"(\\*)(</?(?:[fb]g\s)?[^<>\s]*>)"`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that when logging a message with `opt(colors=True)`, color tags present in the formatting arguments (`args` and `kwargs`) are completely ignored.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This is important if you need to log strings containing markups that might interfere with the color tags (in this case, do not use f-string).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The default values of sink parameters can be entirely customized.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This is particularly useful if you don’t like the log format of the pre-configured sink.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Each of the `add()` default parameter can be modified by setting the `LOGURU_[PARAM]` environment variable.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] For example on Linux: `export LOGURU_FORMAT="{time} - {message}"` or `export LOGURU_DIAGNOSE=NO`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The default levels’ attributes can also be modified by setting the `LOGURU_[LEVEL]_[ATTR]` environment variable.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] For example, on Windows: `setx LOGURU_DEBUG_COLOR "<blue>"` or `setx LOGURU_TRACE_ICON "🚀"`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If you use the `set` command, do not include quotes but escape special symbol as needed, e.g.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] If you want to disable the pre-configured sink, you can set the `LOGURU_AUTOINIT` variable to `False`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] On Linux, you will probably need to edit the `~/.profile` file to make this persistent.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] On Windows, don’t forget to restart your terminal for the change to be taken into account.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Remove a previously added handler and stop sending logs to its sink.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Wait for the end of enqueued messages and asynchronous tasks scheduled by handlers.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This method proceeds in two steps: first it waits for all logging messages added to handlers with `enqueue=True` to be processed, then it returns an object that can be awaited to finalize all logging tasks added to the event loop by coroutine sinks.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] It can be called from non-asynchronous code.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This is especially recommended when the `logger` is utilized with `multiprocessing` to ensure messages put to the internal queue have been properly transmitted before leaving a child process.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The returned object should be awaited before the end of a coroutine executed by `asyncio.run()` or `loop.run_until_complete()` to ensure all asynchronous logging messages are processed.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The function `asyncio.get_running_loop()` is called beforehand, only tasks scheduled in the same loop that the current one will be awaited by the method.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] awaitable – An awaitable object which ensures all asynchronous logging calls are completed when awaited.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Return a decorator to automatically log possibly caught error in wrapped function.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This is useful to ensure unexpected exceptions are logged, the entire program can be wrapped by this method.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This is also very useful to decorate `Thread.run()` methods while using threads to propagate errors to the main logger thread.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that the visibility of variables values (which uses the great `better_exceptions` library from @Qix-) depends on the `diagnose` option of each configured sink.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The returned object can also be used as a context manager.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] decorator / context manager – An object that can be used to decorate a function or as a context manager to log exceptions possibly caught.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Parametrize a logging call to slightly change generated log message.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that it’s not possible to chain `opt()` calls, the last one takes precedence over the others as it will “reset” the options to their default values.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `Logger` – A logger wrapping the core logger, but transforming logged message adequately before sending.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Bind attributes to the `extra` dict of each logged message record.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This is used to add custom context to each logging call.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `Logger` – A logger wrapping the core logger, but which sends record with the customized `extra` dict.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Bind attributes to the context-local `extra` dict while inside the `with` block.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Contrary to `bind()` there is no `logger` returned, the `extra` dict is modified in-place and updated globally.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Most importantly, it uses `contextvars` which means that contextualized values are unique to each threads and asynchronous tasks.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `extra` dict will retrieve its initial state once the context manager is exited.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] context manager / decorator – A context manager (usable as a decorator too) that will bind the attributes once entered and restore the initial state of the `extra` dict while exited.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Attach a function to modify the record dict created by each logging call.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The `patcher` may be used to update the record on-the-fly before it’s propagated to the handlers.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] This allows the “extra” dict to be populated with dynamic values and also permits advanced modifications of the record emitted while logging a message.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The function is called once before sending the log message to the different handlers.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] It is recommended to apply modification on the `record["extra"]` dict rather than on the `record` dict itself, as some values are used internally by *Loguru*, and modify them may produce unexpected results.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The logger can be patched multiple times.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] In this case, the functions are called in the same order as they are added.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `Logger` – A logger wrapping the core logger, but which records are passed through the `patcher` function before being sent to the added handlers.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Add, update or retrieve a logging level.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Logging levels are defined by their `name` to which a severity `no`, an ansi `color` tag and an `icon` are associated and possibly modified at run-time.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To `log()` to a custom level, you should necessarily use its name, the severity number is not linked back to levels name (this implies that several levels can share the same severity).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To add a new level, its `name` and its `no` are required.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] A `color` and an `icon` can also be specified or will be empty by default.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To update an existing level, pass its `name` with the parameters to be changed.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] It is not possible to modify the `no` of a level once it has been added.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To retrieve level information, the `name` solely suffices.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `Level` – A `namedtuple` containing information about the level.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Disable logging of messages coming from `name` module and its children.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Developers of library using *Loguru* should absolutely disable it to avoid disrupting users with unrelated logs messages.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Note that in some rare circumstances, it is not possible for *Loguru* to determine the module’s `__name__` value.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] In such situation, `record["name"]` will be equal to `None`, this is why `None` is also a valid argument.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Enable logging of messages coming from `name` module and its children.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Logging is generally disabled by imported library using *Loguru*, hence this function allows users to receive these messages anyway.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To enable all logs regardless of the module they are coming from, an empty string `""` can be passed.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] It should be noted that `extra` values set using this function are available across all modules, so this is the best way to set overall default values.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] To load the configuration directly from a file, such as JSON or YAML, it is also possible to use the `loguru-config` library developed by @erezinman.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `list` of `int` – A list containing the identifiers of added sinks (if any).
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Parse raw logs and extract each entry as a `dict`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] The logging format has to be specified as the regex `pattern`, it will then be used to parse the `file` and retrieve each entry based on the named groups present in the regex.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] `dict` – The dict mapping regex named groups to matched values, as returned by `re.Match.groupdict()` and optionally converted according to `cast` argument.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `'TRACE'`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `'DEBUG'`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `'INFO'`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `'SUCCESS'`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `'WARNING'`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `'ERROR'`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `'CRITICAL'`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log an 'ERROR'`` message while also capturing the currently handled exception.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Log `message.format(*args, **kwargs)` with severity `level`.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Deprecated function, use `add()` instead.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Deprecated since version 0.2.2: `start()` will be removed in Loguru 1.0.0, it is replaced by `add()` which is a less confusing name.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Deprecated function, use `remove()` instead.
[src:loguru-logging/api-logger] Deprecated since version 0.2.2: `stop()` will be removed in Loguru 1.0.0, it is replaced by `remove()` which is a less confusing name.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:loguru-logging/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:loguru-logging/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] The main concept of Loguru is that **there is one and only one** `logger`.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] For convenience, it is pre-configured and outputs to `stderr` to begin with (but that’s entirely configurable).
[src:loguru-logging/overview] The `logger` is just an interface which dispatches log messages to configured handlers.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] This function should be used to register sinks which are responsible for managing log messages contextualized with a record dict.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] A sink can take many forms: a simple function, a string path, a file-like object, a coroutine function or a built-in Handler.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Note that you may also a previously added handler by using the identifier returned while adding it.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] This is particularly useful if you want to supersede the default `stderr` handler: just call `logger.remove()` to make a fresh start.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] If you want to send logged messages to a file, you just have to use a string path as the sink.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] It is also easily configurable if you need rotating logger, if you want to remove older logs, or if you wish to compress your files at closure.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Loguru favors the much more elegant and powerful `{}` formatting over `%`, logging functions are actually equivalent to `str.format()`.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Have you ever seen your program crashing unexpectedly without seeing anything in the log file?
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Did you ever notice that exceptions occurring in threads were not logged?
[src:loguru-logging/overview] This can be solved using the `catch()` decorator / context manager which ensures that any error is correctly propagated to the `logger`.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Loguru automatically adds colors to your logs if your terminal is compatible.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] You can define your favorite style by using markup tags in the sink format.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] All sinks added to the `logger` are thread-safe by default.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] They are not multiprocess-safe, but you can `enqueue` the messages to ensure logs integrity.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] This same argument can also be used if you want async logging.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Coroutine functions used as sinks are also supported and should be awaited with `complete()`.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Logging exceptions that occur in your code is important to track bugs, but it’s quite useless if you don’t know why it failed.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Loguru helps you identify problems by allowing the entire stack trace to be displayed, including values of variables (thanks `better_exceptions` for this!).
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Note that this feature won’t work on default Python REPL due to unavailable frame data.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] See also: Security considerations when using Loguru.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Want your logs to be serialized for easier parsing or to pass them around?
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Using the `serialize` argument, each log message will be converted to a JSON string before being sent to the configured sink.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Using `bind()` you can contextualize your logger messages by modifying the `extra` record attribute.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Sometime you would like to log verbose information without performance penalty in production, you can use the `opt()` method to achieve this.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Loguru comes with all standard logging levels to which `trace()` and `success()` are added.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Then, just create it by using the `level()` function.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] The standard logging is bloated with arguments like `datefmt` or `msecs`, `%(asctime)s` and `%(created)s`, naive datetimes without timezone information, not intuitive formatting, etc.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Using the logger in your scripts is easy, and you can `configure()` it at start.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] To use Loguru from inside a library, remember to never call `add()` but use `disable()` instead so logging functions become no-op.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] If a developer wishes to see your library’s logs, they can `enable()` it again.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] For additional convenience, you can also use the `loguru-config` library to setup the `logger` directly from a configuration file.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Wish to use built-in logging `Handler` as a Loguru sink?
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Need to propagate Loguru messages to standard `logging`?
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Want to intercept standard `logging` messages toward your Loguru sinks?
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Don’t like the default logger formatting?
[src:loguru-logging/overview] It is often useful to extract specific information from generated logs, this is why Loguru provides a `parse()` method which helps to deal with logs and regexes.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Loguru can easily be combined with the great `apprise` library (must be installed separately) to receive an e-mail when your program fail unexpectedly or to send many other kind of notifications.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] Although logging impact on performances is in most cases negligible, a zero-cost logger would allow to use it anywhere without much concern.
[src:loguru-logging/overview] In an upcoming release, Loguru’s critical functions will be implemented in C for maximum speed.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:loguru-logging/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
